        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We configure the correlator in spectral line to observe the continuum and CO v=0 (3-2). We ask for the minimum frequency resolution and largest 
bandwidth in basebands 1,2 and 4 to study the continuum, while for baseband 3 we ask for a resolution of 0.847 km/s and bandwidth 1.875 GHz to 
search for CO v=0 (3-2) emission without loosing spectral coverage for the continuum.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We need an angular resolution of 0.6 arcsec to search for the double ring structure seen in scattered light images obtained with the Hubble space telescope. These two rings are separated by a distance of ~2 arcsecond. Hence with a resolution of 0.6 we are able to study the gap between the two peaks with a resolution of 3 synthetic beams. 

This resolution level can be achieve in configuration C36-2 in band 7.

Although the disk diameter is 10", according to our CASA simulations a single pointing without ACA observations and with a largest angular scale of 7" 
is sufficient to recover the whole disk with the right intensities value.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We simulated ALMA observations with simobserve in CASA 4.3, using a model image produced using an N-body simulation and radiative transfer code 
that fits the spectral energy distribution of the Source. With a synthetic beam of 0.6 arcsec, we obtained an intensity peak of 150 ujy/beam and mean 
intensity levels of 120 uJy/beam. We request a rms of 12.0 uJy over 7.5 GHz to have a 10 sigma contrast between the disk mean continuum emission 
and the noise level.

We configure the spectral setup in Spectral line mode to cover the CO v=0 (3-2) line with the baseband 3 and see if we can detect any CO emission 
with a resolution of 0.847 km/s without loosing frequency coverage of the continuum. But the total integration time and desired rms is constrained by the 
continuum observation using the agregate Band width.
Since the age of the system, we do not really expect gas to be present, nevertheless, trying to detect it does not impact the continuum sensitivity.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
