    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA continuum mapping in Band 7 of the debris disk surrounding the nearby K dwarf star HD 92945. As revealed by HST, it possesses a double ring structure with a sharp inner edge.

This morphology suggests the presence of a belt-shaping planet located at several tens of AU, but the double ring structure origin remains however unclear. With an age of ~100 Myr, HD 92945 offers a rare opportunity to observe late stages of planetary systems evolution around a low-mass star.

This debris disk has been imaged at 850 microns with SCUBA 2, with a resolution too low to distinguish the double ring structure, but revealing that the disk total flux at this wavelength makes it detectable with ALMA.

The location of HD 92945 is ideal, because a single pointing at 850 microns with ALMA can map the entire debris disk, while achieving a resolution permitting the distinction between the two rings. At this wavelengths, we will probe the distribution of large grains which are little affected by radiation pressure. They will trace the direct gravitational signature of the inferred perturber, allowing to constrain its mass and location, as well as the origin of the double ring structure.</prp:abstract>
